description.narrative:
Being LGBTI in Asia and the Pacific (BLIAP) is a regional programme that addresses inequality, violence and discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression or sex characteristics (SOGI), and promotes universal access to health and social services. The programme is a collaboration between governments, civil society, regional institutions, and other stakeholders to advance the social inclusion of lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and intersex (LGBTI)2 people. It is supported by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), the Embassy of Sweden in Bangkok, the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID), the Australian Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT), the Government of Canada, the Ministry for European Affairs and Equality (Malta) and the Faith in Love Foundation (Hong Kong). The goal of the programme is to promote LGBTI inclusive development in Asia and the Pacific.

The objectives of the programme are:

1. Through community building and empowerment, to support LGBTI individuals to know their rights, and to have access to justice to report human rights violations and end impunity;

2. Through community mobilization and advocacy (with law makers, local governments, judiciary, and NHRIs), to ensure the development and enforcement of protective laws and policies (including anti-violence/anti-discrimination laws and policies);

3. Through community mobilization and engagement with key stakeholders (such as religious organizations, the private sector, law enforcement authorities, educational institutions), to address stigma and discrimination and end harmful practices that fuel human rights violations against LGBTI individuals in public and private settings, and to ensure LGBTI individuals have equal access to public services.
